  "prompt": "How does specific heat and heat capacity differ?",
  "response": "Specific heat and heat capacity are two concepts related to the thermal properties of materials and their ability to absorb heat. While they are related, they have distinct definitions and applications.\n\n### Heat Capacity\nHeat capacity (C) is a measure of the amount of heat energy required to raise the temperature of an entire object or substance by a certain amount, usually 1 degree Celsius (or 1 Kelvin). It is extensive, meaning that it depends on the amount of substance or the size of the object. The SI unit for heat capacity is Joules per degree Celsius (J/\u00b0C) or Joules per Kelvin (J/K).\n\n### Specific Heat\nSpecific heat (often denoted as \\( c \\) or sometimes \\( C_s \\)) is the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one unit mass of a substance by one degree Celsius (or one Kelvin). It is an intensive property, meaning that it is independent of the amount of substance and depends only on the type and phase of the material. The SI unit for specific heat is Joules per kilogram per degree Celsius (J/kg\u00b7\u00b0C) or Joules per kilogram per Kelvin (J/kg\u00b7K).\n\n### Key Differences\n\n1. **Dependency on Mass**:\n   - **Heat Capacity** depends on the amount of material. A larger mass of the substance will have a higher heat capacity.\n   - **Specific Heat** is independent of the amount of material. It is a property of the material itself regardless of how much of it you have.\n\n2. **Units**:\n   - **Heat Capacity**: J/\u00b0C or J/K\n   - **Specific Heat**: J/kg\u00b7\u00b0C or J/kg\u00b7K\n\n3. **Calculation**:\n   - Heat capacity can be calculated using the formula: \\( C = m \\times c \\)\n     where:\n       - \\( C \\) is the heat capacity,\n       - \\( m \\) is the mass of the substance,\n       - \\( c \\) is the specific heat.\n   - Specific heat can be calculated using the formula: \\( c = \\frac{Q}{m \\Delta T} \\)\n     where:\n       - \\( c \\) is the specific heat,\n       - \\( Q \\) is the amount of heat added,\n       - \\( m \\) is the mass of the substance,\n       - \\( \\Delta T \\) is the change in temperature.\n\n### Practical Example\nTo illustrate the difference, consider 1 kilogram of water and 10 kilograms of water. The specific heat of water is about 4.18 J/g\u00b0C. This value remains the same regardless of whether you are considering 1 kg or 10 kg of water. However, the heat capacity of 1 kg of water would be 4180 J/\u00b0C, whereas the heat capacity of 10 kg of water would be 41800 J/\u00b0C.\n\nIn summary, specific heat is a material-specific property that tells you how much energy is needed to change the temperature of a kilogram of substance by 1 \u00b0C, while heat capacity tells you how much energy is required to change the temperature of the whole object/sample you're working with.",
